## The Implement Step — Where Plans Become Protection

The Select step produced a complete, AO-approved System Security Plan. The Implement step — the fourth step of the NIST RMF — is where the security controls documented in that plan are built, configured, and deployed into the actual system.

NIST SP 800-37 Task I-1 asks the organization to implement the security controls specified in the security plan. For a system being authorized for the first time, many technical controls may already be in place — they were implemented during system deployment before the formal RMF process began. The Task I-1 work in that case is not building controls from scratch but verifying that what was deployed matches what the SSP documents, capturing the configuration evidence that the assessment team will need, and completing any controls that are still in progress.

For OpenMRS at MyClinic, the baseline technical controls — encryption, MFA, audit logging, network security, WAF — were implemented during the initial AWS deployment that this project has been documenting throughout. Task I-1 formalizes that implementation by verifying each technical control against its SSP description, documenting the configuration state, and identifying any gaps between the documented intent and the current implementation.

Today I work through the technical control families systematically — not as a high-level overview of what each control type does, but as a verification and documentation exercise that connects the SSP entries from Days 50-51 to the actual configuration state that an assessor would examine.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Task I-1 implementation verification has a specific structure for each control: confirm the control is implemented as documented in the SSP, capture the configuration evidence, identify any discrepancies between the SSP description and the actual configuration, and document discrepancies as either SSP update items (if the implementation is correct but the description is inaccurate) or POA&M items (if the implementation is incomplete or incorrect).

The output of today's work is the implementation evidence package — the collection of configuration records, screenshots, policy exports, and verification records that the assessment team will use as the starting point for their testing.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified Task I-1 for me is the difference between implementing a control and deploying a capability.

AWS provides the capability for dozens of security features — GuardDuty threat detection, Config rule compliance, KMS encryption, WAF protection, CloudTrail logging. A brand-new AWS account with default settings has none of these features enabled. Each capability requires deliberate configuration by the account owner before it is a functioning control.

The implementation verification exercise makes this distinction concrete. For each technical control, the question is not "does AWS offer this?" — the answer is yes for almost everything in the SSP. The question is "is it enabled, is it configured correctly, and does the configuration match what the SSP documents?" Those are three separate questions that require three separate verification steps.

The Capital One breach is the most documented case study for why this matters — AWS provided all the security capabilities; the gap was in which capabilities were configured and how. Task I-1 is the process of verifying that the OpenMRS deployment has made the right configuration choices for every capability it relies on, and documented them at the level of detail that lets an assessor independently verify the configuration.

