## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The SSH restriction discrepancy found today — port 22 open to 0.0.0.0/0 — is exactly the configuration gap that enabled the **2019 Capital One breach** via a different entry point. In the Capital One case, the Server Side Request Forgery vulnerability allowed the attacker to reach the EC2 metadata service and retrieve temporary credentials. A more broadly applicable lesson from that incident: default configurations and leftover open ports from development environments are among the most commonly exploited entry points in cloud infrastructure.

The AWS Config rule restricted-ssh exists precisely because unrestricted SSH access is such a common misconfiguration. The fact that the Config rule would have flagged today's SSH finding — had it been running and monitored before today's verification — illustrates the value of the automated continuous monitoring established in Day 52. The Config rule would have caught this misconfiguration as a NON_COMPLIANT finding the moment it was created, not days or weeks later during a manual verification exercise.

This is the feedback loop that Task I-1 and the continuous monitoring strategy are designed to create: implementation verification catches gaps before assessment, and continuous monitoring catches drift after authorization. Both are necessary because configuration gaps can be introduced at deployment and configuration drift can occur at any time afterward.

