## What I Am Still Thinking About

During the Inspector finding review today, one of the HIGH findings was a Python library vulnerability in a package that is installed on the EC2 instance but not used by OpenMRS. I documented it as accepted risk with a compensating control notation.

But I want to think more carefully about whether "not used by OpenMRS" is a sufficient basis for accepting the risk. If the Python library is installed on the system, it is part of the attack surface — even if OpenMRS does not call it directly, an attacker who gains code execution on the EC2 instance could potentially exploit the vulnerable library. The argument for remediation is: the safest state is to remove unused packages entirely (reducing the attack surface) rather than accepting risk from packages that happen to be unused.

The NIST SP 800-53 CM-7 control — Least Functionality — requires that the system be configured to provide only essential capabilities. An unused Python library is exactly the type of unnecessary functionality that CM-7 addresses. I should revisit the POA&M entry for this finding and change the disposition from "accepted risk" to "remediate — remove unused package" with a timeline that matches the HIGH severity schedule. This is a more defensible position and is consistent with the least functionality principle.

